

a = """\nOSI & TCP IP Model Notes

--------------------------------------------

Layer 7: Application (Away)
Layer 6: Presentation (Pizza)
Layer 5: Session (Sausage)
Layer 4: Transport (Throw)
Layer 3: Network (Not)
Layer 2: Data (Do)
Layer 1: Physical (Please)

--------------------------------------------

* TCP/IP Model is a substitue for OSI
* The persons that created the internet focused on two protocols. TCP & IP


* Going DOWN(7-1) the stack of layers is called "Encapsulating"
* Going UP(1-7) the stack of layers is called "Decapsulation"

* Layer 7, 6, & 5 can be grouped together. by the time we get to the transport layer, these three layers produce a PDU (Protocol Data Unit) will be in 
    binary number with the data all prepared for transport
    * First 3 layers (7,6,5) are accomplished in the application layer of TCP/IP

* Applications make requests, services receive them.
* The way we identify them is through port addresses. There is a source, and a destination


* At the TRANSPORT layer the PDU is called segments. because it breaks down the data into segments
* We use segments for security, performance, and to allow multiple communications to occur relatively at the same time called "Multiplexy"
* TCP & UDP protocols from layer 4 -> 3 most popular protocol. 
* Transferring from the Transport layer to the Network Layer, IP tells us how to take the segments and turn them into a packet w/ a
    source and destination

* Definition of a network- two or more devices connected
* Have to figure out what devices are on the network, sources and destinations




*DATA LINK LAYER:
* Add a frame. Segment --> packet --> frame
* Idea is to connect all of the logical stuff from previous layers to the physical layer. Abstract -> Real, using standards
* Ethernet is an example of protocol || standard, IEEE 802.11ac covers all bandwith for wifi. Uses full potential of wireless router


* Physical layer:
    bits -> signal



TCP/IP Model

* Application Layer:(All in the software. Groups first three layers of OSI together, 5,6 & 7) produce data. interconnected, 
connects to transport layer, which produces segments. what applications and services are we talking about 
* Transport: --> segments
* Internetwork: --> packets
* Network Access Layer: groups last two layers (physical and data)"""

print(a)

